                <h1>Hazelwood School District v. Kuhlmeier: Key Case Insights</h1>
                <p>In Hazelwood School District v. Kuhlmeier (1988), the U.S. Supreme Court addressed students' rights to free speech in school-sponsored publications. The case arose when principal Robert Reynolds censored articles in the student newspaper, leading to a legal dispute. The Court ruled that schools can regulate student speech if they have legitimate educational concerns.</p>
